1
00:00:15,615 --> 00:00:19,551
(SINGING UPBEAT POP SONG)

2
00:01:09,035 --> 00:01:11,003
(ON VOICEMAIL) This is Jason's cell.
You know what to do.

3
00:01:11,071 --> 00:01:14,040
Hey there, Major Danville, it's me.

4
00:01:14,374 --> 00:01:17,070
Don't worry. I'll be there
in time for your big moment.

5
00:01:18,344 --> 00:01:22,906
By the way, we've been married
for five years. What?

6
00:01:23,216 --> 00:01:26,083
I just love you so much.
I can't wait to go on vacation.

7
00:01:28,488 --> 00:01:29,887
(MOUTHING POP SONG)

8
00:01:33,093 --> 00:01:36,961
Yeah, I'm here for the NAA
Collier ceremony thing. You know...

9
00:01:37,030 --> 00:01:38,691
-Yes, ma'am. ID?
-Sure.

10
00:01:43,870 --> 00:01:48,898
Wow! F-22 Raptor. That's my favorite.
Nice little fighter jet.

11
00:01:48,975 --> 00:01:51,000
-Yes, ma'am.
-Thanks.

12
00:01:57,817 --> 00:02:00,115
(SALLY SINGING UPBEAT POP SONG)

13
00:02:08,528 --> 00:02:12,988
Excuse me, I'm sorry. I'm just kind
of in a rush here. Excuse me.

14
00:02:17,637 --> 00:02:18,934
Hey. How you all doing today?

15
00:02:19,973 --> 00:02:23,170
LINDFORD: On behalf of
the National Aeronautic Association,

16
00:02:23,243 --> 00:02:27,373
for his ground-breaking
new and far safer design

17
00:02:27,447 --> 00:02:30,883
of a diffuser for the scramjet engine,

18
00:02:30,950 --> 00:02:37,549
it is my honor to present Jason Danville
with the prestigious Collier Trophy.

19
00:02:37,624 --> 00:02:38,955
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

20
00:02:39,025 --> 00:02:40,754
(WHOOPING)

21
00:02:42,629 --> 00:02:44,256
Way to go, baby!

22
00:02:44,430 --> 00:02:46,762
Thank you, ladies and gentlemen.

23
00:02:46,833 --> 00:02:51,463
I'd like to thank General Lindford
and the National Aeronautic Association,

24
00:02:51,538 --> 00:02:55,030
and most importantly,
I'd like to thank my wife Sally.

25
00:02:55,208 --> 00:02:57,472
(ALL APPLAUDING)

26
00:02:59,679 --> 00:03:02,978
Before I was an aeronautical engineer,
I was an Air Force pilot.

27
00:03:03,049 --> 00:03:06,644
In fact,
I even flew in a few of these events.

28
00:03:06,719 --> 00:03:09,449
And we used to joke
that we weren't in the Air Force,

29
00:03:09,522 --> 00:03:10,614
we were in show business.

30
00:03:10,990 --> 00:03:13,151
And you know what the first rule
of entertainment is?

31
00:03:16,362 --> 00:03:17,989
Show, don't tell.

32
00:03:18,097 --> 00:03:19,928
(JET PLANES SOARING)

33
00:03:26,606 --> 00:03:28,267
(ALL APPLAUDING)

34
00:03:33,046 --> 00:03:36,072
-I'm so syked to go to Tahiti.
-Yeah.

35
00:03:36,950 --> 00:03:40,647
Best diving in the world.
Seriously, wall-to-wall coral.

36
00:03:40,720 --> 00:03:41,914
Haven't been there since I was a kid,

37
00:03:41,988 --> 00:03:44,548
but apparently the oceanic drop-offs
at Tahiti Nui

38
00:03:44,624 --> 00:03:46,683
are supposed to be absolutely stunning.

39
00:03:46,759 --> 00:03:47,885
I'm serious.

40
00:03:47,961 --> 00:03:50,191
The most serious man I know.

41
00:03:50,396 --> 00:03:51,761
-Come on.
-Let's get out of here!

42
00:03:56,669 --> 00:04:00,503
-All right, sweetie, are you ready?
-Yeah, I'm ready. I'm ready.

43
00:04:00,573 --> 00:04:01,699
Really?

44
00:04:01,774 --> 00:04:04,675
-Yeah, I'm excited.
-This is going to be great.

45
00:04:04,744 --> 00:04:05,972
-Are you packed?
-Of course.

46
00:04:06,045 --> 00:04:09,981
Well, you know, sort of.
Not really, but...

47
00:04:10,049 --> 00:04:11,448
Happy anniversary, baby.

48
00:04:11,517 --> 00:04:12,506
SALLY: I love you.

49
00:04:36,042 --> 00:04:38,567
(TELEPHONES RINGING)

50
00:04:43,182 --> 00:04:46,174
Forget about it. Don't answer that.
We're out of here, sweetie.

51
00:04:48,888 --> 00:04:50,048
SALLY: Hello.

52
00:04:53,793 --> 00:04:56,057
All right, are you ready?

53
00:04:57,830 --> 00:04:59,320
Sal?

54
00:05:02,302 --> 00:05:04,532
(STUTTERING) What is it? What happened?

55
00:05:05,772 --> 00:05:10,368
Yeah. No, that's right.
Uh-huh. Thank you.

56
00:05:10,810 --> 00:05:14,803
We appreciate it
and, yes, happy skies to you, too.

57
00:05:15,548 --> 00:05:16,947
(HANGS UP)

58
00:05:18,151 --> 00:05:19,448
All right, well,
we're good with insurance.

59
00:05:19,519 --> 00:05:22,579
We just have to use
the tickets within a year.

60
00:05:24,724 --> 00:05:26,692
JASON: So young.
SALLY: Can't believe it.

61
00:05:26,759 --> 00:05:29,819
She was my mentor.
My oldest friend, you know.

62
00:05:34,667 --> 00:05:37,795
Could have been mechanical failure,
fog, turbulence, they're not sure.

63
00:05:37,870 --> 00:05:38,859
This is Africa.

64
00:05:39,505 --> 00:05:42,201
-How's that?
-Oh, it's just an expression.

65
00:05:42,275 --> 00:05:43,799
This is Africa,

66
00:05:43,876 --> 00:05:45,503
a place where you rarely find out
how a thing happens or why...

67
00:05:45,578 --> 00:05:49,639
-The point is, there were no survivors.
-Yes, that's the point.

68
00:05:49,716 --> 00:05:52,310
Scott will fill you in
on the legal implications

69
00:05:52,385 --> 00:05:55,445
and then I'll follow up
with the practical applications.

70
00:05:55,521 --> 00:05:57,386
Okay, okay, can we...

71
00:05:57,724 --> 00:06:00,284
What about this application
or implications or what?

72
00:06:00,360 --> 00:06:03,193
Teresa and her husband Frank
left four children.

73
00:06:03,262 --> 00:06:05,787
Peace Corps brought them
back to the U.S. a month ago.

74
00:06:12,038 --> 00:06:15,235
Wait. You're not going
where I think you're going. Are you?

75
00:06:15,308 --> 00:06:20,712
This is their final will.
And right here...

76
00:06:21,914 --> 00:06:24,041
That's your name, isn't it?

77
00:06:24,917 --> 00:06:27,613
Yeah, I haven't...
I haven't seen her in...

78
00:06:27,687 --> 00:06:29,848
That was a long time ago
and her daughter was just two...

79
00:06:29,922 --> 00:06:33,016
Of possible guardians,
the immediate families are out.

80
00:06:33,092 --> 00:06:35,560
Parents have passed away,
Frank was an only child,

81
00:06:35,628 --> 00:06:38,096
Teresa's sister is on her second tour
in Afghanistan.

82
00:06:38,164 --> 00:06:39,358
You were next in line.

83
00:06:39,432 --> 00:06:41,832
Teresa and Frank believed
that if anything should happen,

84
00:06:41,901 --> 00:06:44,233
they could entrust you
with the care of their kids.

85
00:06:44,303 --> 00:06:45,292
Well, something has happened.

86
00:06:45,705 --> 00:06:47,730
Excuse me, Dorothy, right?

87
00:06:49,175 --> 00:06:52,581
Of the Ohio Family...
I'm sorry, this is just...

88
00:06:52,583 --> 00:06:54,408
This is a lot to take in all at once...

89
00:06:54,480 --> 00:06:59,586
It is the Ohio Center
of Family Protection,

90
00:06:59,800 --> 00:07:02,311
-and it's on the card that I gave you.
-Right, right, right.

91
00:07:03,087 --> 00:07:04,784
Okay, so here's the thing.

92
00:07:04,857 --> 00:07:07,621
Tezzie's my oldest friend. I would do
anything in the world for her,

93
00:07:07,693 --> 00:07:12,323
but the truth is,
we're completely unsuited to be parents.

94
00:07:12,432 --> 00:07:15,094
I mean, not even to take the kids.

95
00:07:15,168 --> 00:07:20,367
We have careers, we travel, 
we barely even have time for each other.

96
00:07:20,440 --> 00:07:23,034
And kids, not in the playbook.

97
00:07:24,744 --> 00:07:25,802
Playbook?

98
00:07:25,945 --> 00:07:30,780
-You know what I mean.
-Yeah, I can't cook. I mean, I can't.

99
00:07:30,850 --> 00:07:33,648
I don't know the first thing about kids
or what to do with them.

100
00:07:33,719 --> 00:07:34,708
That's two of us.

101
00:07:34,787 --> 00:07:37,756
Nobody is trying to force you
to be parents...

102
00:07:37,824 --> 00:07:39,553
All right, then, I guess that's that.

103
00:07:39,659 --> 00:07:42,219
And I don't suppose
you'd be interested in seeing them.

104
00:07:43,629 --> 00:07:47,065
Wait, they're here? Little Jordan...

105
00:07:47,633 --> 00:07:50,067
They were brought in
two weeks ago from D.C.

106
00:07:50,136 --> 00:07:51,626
They're staying in a group home.

107
00:07:51,704 --> 00:07:54,969
Okay, so you just assumed
that we'd take them.

108
00:07:55,975 --> 00:07:57,272
Frankly, yes.

109
00:07:57,610 --> 00:08:00,101
As per your commitment to your friend.

110
00:08:00,613 --> 00:08:02,513
(SIGHS)

111
00:08:03,349 --> 00:08:06,716
My wife and I would like to have
a private conversation, please.

112
00:08:07,186 --> 00:08:08,710
Yes, of course.

113
00:08:11,457 --> 00:08:12,754
-(DOOR CLOSES)
-Wow.

114
00:08:12,959 --> 00:08:14,085
-I can't believe this is happening.
-Heavy.

115
00:08:14,160 --> 00:08:15,752
-I can't believe this is happening...
-Very interesting.

116
00:08:15,828 --> 00:08:17,056
-Honestly...
-No.

117
00:08:17,129 --> 00:08:19,791
No way we can adopt four kids. No way.
This is just not who we are.

118
00:08:19,899 --> 00:08:21,867
-I know. You're telling me?
-I feel terrible. They're right.

119
00:08:21,968 --> 00:08:23,458
I have an obligation.
I have an obligation...

120
00:08:23,536 --> 00:08:26,801
-Maybe there's something...
-What? What?

121
00:08:26,873 --> 00:08:28,431
I don't know.

122
00:08:29,976 --> 00:08:32,444
I mean, they're kids.

123
00:08:33,112 --> 00:08:36,445
We're not going to feel good about
ourselves unless we do something, right?

124
00:08:36,516 --> 00:08:40,179
And maybe we do something...

125
00:08:42,889 --> 00:08:43,878
-Temporarily.
-Temporary?

126
00:08:43,956 --> 00:08:47,119
-Yeah, until they find a real home.
-A real family.

127
00:08:47,193 --> 00:08:51,892
Right, a real family.
It'd be better than a group home.

128
00:08:51,964 --> 00:08:53,056
Yeah.

129
00:08:54,333 --> 00:08:55,527
I hope.

130
00:08:59,171 --> 00:09:00,763
And that's little Jordan?

131
00:09:02,775 --> 00:09:06,302
Impressive young lady. Hasn't
smiled much since she's been here,

132
00:09:06,379 --> 00:09:08,040
but then who could blame her?

133
00:09:08,414 --> 00:09:10,109
The tiny one is Sung Lee.

134
00:09:10,216 --> 00:09:12,810
She was adopted from China
when she was a year old.

135
00:09:12,885 --> 00:09:15,285
Javier is 15, born in Guatemala.

136
00:09:15,354 --> 00:09:18,084
He was abandoned when he was three
and ended up on the streets.

137
00:09:18,157 --> 00:09:20,853
Teresa and Frank
adopted him five years ago.

138
00:09:20,927 --> 00:09:24,522
And the boy is Kaleb,
adopted in Uganda when he was four.

139
00:09:24,697 --> 00:09:27,962
Jordan. Hi, I'm Sally.

140
00:09:32,705 --> 00:09:35,105
I'm so sorry about your parents.

141
00:09:36,409 --> 00:09:37,467
Thank you.

142
00:09:38,210 --> 00:09:40,337
I loved your mother very much.

143
00:09:41,113 --> 00:09:42,273
So did we.

144
00:09:45,718 --> 00:09:46,707
Hi.

145
00:09:47,286 --> 00:09:49,846
-I'm Kaleb.
-Hi, Kaleb,

146
00:09:49,922 --> 00:09:51,981
I'm Sally. It's wonderful to meet you.

147
00:09:55,194 --> 00:09:58,163
-Hi.
-Hi, Sung Lee, I'm Sally.

148
00:09:58,998 --> 00:10:00,465
I was your mommy's good friend.

149
00:10:00,600 --> 00:10:01,897
(GIGGLES)

150
00:10:03,836 --> 00:10:06,430
-This is Javier.
-Hi, Javier.

151
00:10:06,906 --> 00:10:08,931
-Hello.
-SALLY: It's good to meet you.

152
00:10:09,008 --> 00:10:12,000
You must be Jordan. I'm Jason. Hi.

153
00:10:12,445 --> 00:10:14,606
That troublemaker must be Kaleb, huh?

154
00:10:14,747 --> 00:10:15,907
I'm not a troublemaker.

155
00:10:16,349 --> 00:10:18,476
All right, throttle back.
I was just kidding.

156
00:10:19,285 --> 00:10:22,618
So you're all going to come
and stay with us.

157
00:10:22,722 --> 00:10:24,246
Would you like that?

158
00:10:29,261 --> 00:10:31,388
(CHUCKLING) Yes. Yes. Yes.

159
00:10:47,680 --> 00:10:49,011
(SCATTING)

160
00:11:02,194 --> 00:11:06,290
Hey, you. (SIGHS)
How are those bunk beds coming along?

161
00:11:06,365 --> 00:11:09,061
Oh, you know,
academy, MIT, Collier Trophy...

162
00:11:09,135 --> 00:11:12,104
-What could possibly go wrong?
-Yeah, right.

163
00:11:12,171 --> 00:11:13,229
Yeah, what could go wrong?

164
00:11:15,241 --> 00:11:19,803
Jason, how are we going to do this?
I mean, even for a week? I...

165
00:11:19,879 --> 00:11:21,676
My mom, you know, she was great.

166
00:11:21,747 --> 00:11:24,181
I don't know how she did it.
I just didn't pay attention, I guess.

167
00:11:24,250 --> 00:11:26,047
-Guess I was just so focused on myself...
-I know.

168
00:11:26,118 --> 00:11:29,781
Tell me about. All I wanted to do is fly,
and once I did, I never looked back.

169
00:11:29,855 --> 00:11:31,049
(DOORBELL RINGING)

170
00:11:31,123 --> 00:11:33,216
That's them. They're here.

171
00:11:34,527 --> 00:11:35,551
Hi, Dorothy.

172
00:11:36,762 --> 00:11:39,663
-Hi, everyone.
-Interesting place..

173
00:11:39,732 --> 00:11:42,792
Yeah, it's a little tecked out,
but it's my studio.

174
00:11:42,902 --> 00:11:44,529
-Yeah, we live upstairs.
-Uh-huh.

175
00:11:44,837 --> 00:11:45,997
Thank you, Auntie Sally.

176
00:11:46,605 --> 00:11:48,004
SALLY: "Auntie" Sally?

177
00:11:48,074 --> 00:11:51,475
DOROTHY: Ugandan custom.
Don't use "Mr." and "Mrs." so much.

178
00:11:54,647 --> 00:11:55,773
(FEEDBACK ON STEREO)

179
00:11:55,848 --> 00:11:57,509
You've got a lot of stuff.

180
00:11:57,583 --> 00:12:00,518
Oh, let's not play that right now.

181
00:12:02,822 --> 00:12:06,758
-Let me go! Let me go! Let me go!
-All right, I'm letting you go.

182
00:12:08,894 --> 00:12:10,088
Why don't we go upstairs?

183
00:12:10,396 --> 00:12:11,693
Here. Let me help you with this.

184
00:12:14,934 --> 00:12:18,097
Okay, guys, just follow me, all right?

185
00:12:21,741 --> 00:12:23,231
See you soon.

186
00:12:26,078 --> 00:12:27,306
Thanks, Dorothy.

187
00:12:27,546 --> 00:12:28,843
You're welcome, Jordan.

188
00:12:33,753 --> 00:12:34,845
(EXCLAIMING)

189
00:12:38,557 --> 00:12:44,018
Okay, so I have identification,
travel visas and medical for you,

190
00:12:44,430 --> 00:12:48,025
-and here is information on Uganda.
-Oh. Good idea.

191
00:12:48,601 --> 00:12:49,727
What are you making?

192
00:12:50,102 --> 00:12:53,902
Something resembling a smoothie.

193
00:12:54,540 --> 00:12:56,235
(BLENDER WHlRRING)

194
00:12:57,743 --> 00:12:59,870
And even if this is
a temporary arrangement,

195
00:12:59,945 --> 00:13:02,743
it's important that they transition
as quickly as possible.

196
00:13:02,815 --> 00:13:05,978
So I've made appointments for you
at two schools in your area,

197
00:13:06,051 --> 00:13:07,746
elementary and high school.

198
00:13:07,953 --> 00:13:08,942
Great.

199
00:13:10,656 --> 00:13:13,454
-I don't want any of that.
-JASON: Are you sure?

200
00:13:13,526 --> 00:13:16,086
It's really good.
It makes you all happy inside.

201
00:13:22,568 --> 00:13:25,799
You and I both know
Jason and I aren't cut out for this.

202
00:13:25,905 --> 00:13:27,463
We don't want these kids to get attached,

203
00:13:27,540 --> 00:13:31,374
so the sooner we can find them
another family, the better.

204
00:13:31,677 --> 00:13:34,612
It's not easy to place
the four of them together,

205
00:13:34,680 --> 00:13:38,241
but I do have some leads,
so I'll call you as soon as I can.

206
00:13:38,417 --> 00:13:39,907
-Appreciate it.
-Thank you.

207
00:13:39,985 --> 00:13:40,974
You're welcome.

208
00:13:49,061 --> 00:13:51,586
(SPEAKING FOREIGN LANGUAGE)

209
00:13:55,734 --> 00:13:59,192
So this looks like an interesting game.
What's it called?

210
00:13:59,271 --> 00:14:01,831
Omweso.
It's the national board game of Uganda.

211
00:14:03,042 --> 00:14:04,031
How do you play?

212
00:14:04,577 --> 00:14:06,772
You start on your side
and you start sowing your seeds.

213
00:14:06,846 --> 00:14:09,076
-It's easy.
-Doesn't look so easy to me.

214
00:14:09,148 --> 00:14:10,376
I always win.

215
00:14:10,449 --> 00:14:13,043
-That's because Mom and Dad let you win.
-Liar!

216
00:14:13,385 --> 00:14:15,182
(SPEAKING FOREIGN LANGUAGE)

217
00:14:15,321 --> 00:14:16,788
(CLATTERING)

218
00:14:19,358 --> 00:14:22,259
Look, I think we should get settled in,

219
00:14:22,361 --> 00:14:27,298
and then maybe we can think about
maybe making some dinner.

220
00:14:27,633 --> 00:14:30,966
I have a better idea.
Let's just order something in.

221
00:14:31,971 --> 00:14:32,960
SALLY: Great idea.

222
00:14:33,706 --> 00:14:35,503
I can help you prepare a meal.

223
00:14:35,574 --> 00:14:39,010
No. No, no, it's okay.
We'll just order some pizza?

224
00:14:39,078 --> 00:14:41,205
Thai or Chinese...
Whatever you guys like, we can...

225
00:14:41,547 --> 00:14:43,913
Dorothy told us you can't cook.

226
00:14:45,551 --> 00:14:46,677
She told you that?

227
00:14:48,254 --> 00:14:51,052
I love to cook, especially for
my family. I can help you.

228
00:14:51,123 --> 00:14:52,522
Even me.

229
00:14:52,591 --> 00:14:55,560
(CHUCKLES) In our family,
the women always prepare meals together.

230
00:14:57,363 --> 00:15:00,958
Okay, well, Jordan, I mean,
in America, you know,

231
00:15:01,033 --> 00:15:05,026
lately, the whole gender thing,
men actually can cook these days.

232
00:15:05,104 --> 00:15:06,093
They, like, you know...

233
00:15:08,707 --> 00:15:13,906
Yeah. Yeah.
Let's... Let's give it a try.

234
00:15:14,647 --> 00:15:17,639
Okay, gentlemen, this is it.
Your quarters.

235
00:15:18,517 --> 00:15:20,451
You got a little washroom over here
to the right,

236
00:15:20,519 --> 00:15:22,487
you got the bunk beds. Who wants tops?

237
00:15:22,554 --> 00:15:24,488
-Me.
-You okay with that?

238
00:15:24,990 --> 00:15:26,218
Mmm-hmm.

239
00:15:26,392 --> 00:15:31,694
All right. We've got exercise cycles,
